Macro invertebrate diversity and abundance

This file summarizes macro invertebrate (ie. crabs, seastars, nudibranchs) data from sea grass monitoring transects. It was created by ZLM Nov 2015 (based on inverts.R by MV) for analysis of 2014 and 2015 monitoring data, but with the goal of being generalized to use for future years data as well. Created by ZLM Nov 2015, it is based on inverts.R goal: grazer abundance/msq ## Setup Remove all objects for a clean start!

Formatting

Before summarizing and making figures we will reformat/add some factors to match with the other parts of the monitoring dataset, before printing a table with counts by site, ### Renaming and adding factors The variable Site_ID is currently formatted inconsistently, and the region,variables is missing; we’ll fix these using dplyr::mutate, and some ifelse statements.

inverts <- invert %>%  # with growth df...
  mutate(site_id = as.factor(ifelse(Site_ID == "SC", "CS",
                          ifelse(Site_ID == "LC", "CL",
                                 ifelse(Site_ID == "NT", "TN",
                                        as.character(Site_ID))))),
         site    = ifelse(site_id == "CL", "Choked Lower",
                             ifelse(site_id == "CS", "Choked Sandspit",
                                    ifelse(site_id == "TB", "Triquet Bay",
                                           ifelse(site_id == "TN", "Triquet North",
                                                  ifelse(site_id == "GW", "Goose Southwest",
                                                         ifelse(site_id == "GE", "Goose Southeast",
                                                                ifelse(site_id == "MS", "McMullin South",
                                                                       ifelse(site_id == "MN", "McMullin North",
                                                                              NA)))))))),
         region = as.factor(ifelse(site_id == "CS" | site_id == "CL", "Choked",
                         ifelse(site_id == "TB" | site_id == "TN", "Triquet",
                                ifelse(site_id == "GE" | site_id == "GW", "Goose",
                                       "McMullin")))))

Adding absences to the dataset

The in 2014 and 2015 the survey data only includes observations (presence only data). This results in biased abundance estimates; the loop found below goes through each transect, and checks if all the species were observed. If a species were not observed on a transect, a ‘zero’ observation will be added in. This way, abundance is not conditional on observation, and should no longer be biased.

# make species list
inverts.spp <- subset(unique(inverts$Common), !grepl("unknown", unique(inverts$Common)))
# create unique transect factor
inverts$unique.tran <- with(inverts, as.factor(paste(site, Transect, Time_Start, Diver, sep = "::")))
uniqueTran <- unique(inverts$unique.tran)

# for each site...
for (i in 1:length(uniqueTran)) {
  tmp.invert.tran <-
    subset(inverts, unique.tran %in% uniqueTran[i]) 
  
  tmp.metadata <- 
    tmp.invert.tran %>%
    # group_by(year, day, region, site, site_id, Transect, survey, diver, mode,
    #          tran_length, tran_type, time_start, time_end, tide_start,
    #          tide_end, vis_ft, current_cat, depth_m, unique.tran) %>%
    group_by(Date, Site, Site_ID, Diver, Mode, Transect, Depth_m, Time_Start, site_id,
             site, region, unique.tran) %>%
    summarise() 
  
  tmp.metadata$Species   <- NA
  tmp.metadata$Common    <- NA
  tmp.metadata$Length_cm <- NA
  tmp.metadata$Estimate  <- 0
  tmp.metadata$Notes     <- "implicit zero"
  
  # for each invert species...
  for (j in 1:length(inverts.spp)) {
    # if invert species j does not show up in any row, add new row
    # if (length(grep(paste0("^", inverts.spp[j], "$") tmp.invert.tran$Common)) == 0) {
    if (length(which(tmp.invert.tran$Common == inverts.spp[j])) == 0) {
      
      tmp.metadata$Common <- inverts.spp[j]
      inverts <- rbind(inverts, tmp.metadata)
    } else { # if invert species j is present, move on
      next
    }
  }
}

Defining taxonomic subsets

Here we’ll subset the invertebrate dataset into a couple smaller groups of interest: crabs, nudibranchs, seastars, and everything else, for a more indepth look.

invert.crab <- subset(inverts, Common %in% c("Cryptic_Kelp_crab",
                                            "Kelp_crab",
                                            "Helmet_Crab",
                                            "Red_Rock_Crab",
                                            "Dungeness",
                                            "Furrowed_crab"))

invert.nudi <- subset(inverts, Common %in% c("Hooded_Nudibranch",
                                            "Frosted_nudibranch",
                                            "Leopard_nudibranch",
                                            "Opalescent_Nudibranch",
                                            "Orange_amd_white_tipped_nudi"))

invert.star <- subset(inverts, Common %in% c("Sunflower_Star",
                                            "Leather_Star",
                                            "Giant_Pink_Star",
                                            "Mottled_Star"))
